text=BOOK XXIII. %0a%0aTHE REMEDIES DERIVED FROM THE CULTIVATED TREES. %0a%0aCHAP. 1 . ( 1 .) -INTRODUCTION. %0a%0aWe have now set forth the various properties, medicinal or %0aotherwise, as well of the cereals as of the other productions %0awhich lie u[)Oid the surface of the earth, for the purpose either %0aof serving us for food, or for the gratification of our senses %0awith their flo\vers or perfumes. lu the trees, however, %0aPomona has entered the lists with them, and has imparted %0acertain medicinal properties to the fruits as they hang. Kot con¬ %0atent with protecting and nourishing, under the shadow of the %0atrees, the various plants which w'e have* already described, %0aslie would even appear to be indignant, as it were, at the %0athought that w'^e should derive more succour from those pro¬ %0aductions which are further removed from the canopy of heaven, %0aand which have only come into use in times comparative!}' re¬ %0acent. For she bids man bear in mind that it was the fruits of %0athe trees wliich formed his fii’st nourishment, and that it was %0atliose which first led him to look upwards towards the heavens: %0aand not only this, but she reminds him, too, that even still it %0ais quite possible for him to derive his aliment from the trees, %0awithout being indebted to grain for his subsistence. %0a%0aCHAP. 2 . -THE VINE. %0a%0aBut, by Hercules ! it is the vine more particularly to wdiich %0ashe has accorded these medicinal properties, as though she %0awere not contented with her generosity in providing it w'ith %0asuch delicious flavours, and perfumes, and essences, in its om- %0aphacium, its oenanthe, and its massaris, preparations upon %0awhich W'e have already® enlarged. “ It is to me, she says, %0a“ that man is indebted for the greater part of his enjoyments, %0a%0a• In contradistinction to the fruits which hang from trees. %0a%0a* See B. xvii. c. 18. ® In xii. cc. 60 and 61. %0a%0a%0a458 %0a%0a%0aPLINy’s NA.TUUAL UI3T0IIY. %0a%0a%0a[liook XXIII, %0a%0a%0ait is I that produce for him tlie flowing wine and the trickling %0aoil, it is I that ripen the date and other fruits in numhers so %0avaried ; and all this, not insisting, like the earth, on their pur¬ %0achase at the cost of fatigues and labours. No necessity do I %0acreate for ploughing with the aid of oxen, for beating out %0aupon the threshing-floor, or for bruising under the millstone, %0aand all in order that man may earn his food at some indefinite %0atime by this vast expenditure of toil. As for me, all my gifts %0aare presented to him ready prepared: for no anxieties or %0afatigues do they call, but, on the contrary, they offer them¬ %0aselves spontaneously, and even fall to the ground, if man %0ashould be too indolent to reach them as they hang.” Vying %0aeven with herself, Pomona has done still more for our juac- %0atical advantage than for the mere gratification of our pleasures %0aand caprices. [ %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 3.—THE LEAVES AND SHOOTS OF THE VINE : SEVEN %0a%0a%0aREMEDIES. %0a%0a%0a^The leaves and shoots of the vine, employed with polenta, %0aallay head-ache and reduce inflammations :® the leaves, too, %0aapplied b}' themselves with cold water, are good for burning %0apains in the stomach ; and, used with barley-meal, are excel¬ %0alent applications for diseases of the joints. The shoots, beaten %0aup and applied, have the property of drying up all kinds of %0arunning tumours, and the juice extracted from them is used %0aas an injection for the cure of dysentery. The tears of the %0avine, M^hich would appear to be a sort of gum, will heal le¬ %0aprous sores, lichens, and itch-scabs, if treated first with nitre : %0aused with oil, and applied frequently to superfluous hairs, they %0aact as a depilatory, those more particularly which exude from %0atlie vine when burnt in a green state : this last liquid has the %0aeffect, too, of removing warts. An infusion of the shoots in %0awater, taken in drink, is good for persons troubled with spitting %0aof blood, and for the fainting fits which sometimes ensue upon %0aconception. %0a%0a* All this passage is found in Dioscorides, B. v. c. 1, who probably %0aborrowed it from the same sources as our autlior. %0a%0a* Fee remarks, that all the statements here made as to the medicinal %0aproperties of the vine arc entirely unfounded, except that with reference %0ato the bark of the vine : as it contains a small quantity of tannin, it might %0apossibly, in certain cases, arrest haemorrhage. %0a%0a%0aCliap. 4.] %0a%0a%0aOMPUACtUM. %0a%0a%0a459 %0a%0a%0aIhe bai’k of the vine and the dried leaves arrest the flo^vLng %0aof blood from wouiids, and make the sores cicatrize more %0arapidly. The juice of the white vine,® extracted from it while %0agreen, effectually removes cutaneous’ eruptions. The ashes® %0aof tlie cuttings of vines, and of the husks of the grapes, ap¬ %0aplied with vinegar, are curative of condylomata and diseases %0aof the fundament; as also of sprains, burns, and swellings of %0athe spleen, applied with rose-oil, rue, and vinegar. Used with %0awine, but without oil, they make a fomentation for erysipelas %0aand parts of the body which are chafed; they act as a depila¬ %0atory also.® For affections of the spleen the ashes of vine- %0acuttings, moistened with vinegar, are administered in drink, %0abeing taken in doses of two cyathi in warm water; after which %0atlie patient must take due care to lie upon the side in which %0athe spleen is situate. %0a%0aThe tendrils, too, which the vine throws out as it climbs, %0abeaten up in water and drunk, have the effect of arresting %0ahabitual vomiting. The ashes of the vine, used with stale %0aaxle-grease, are good for tumours, act as a detergent upon fis¬ %0atulas, and speedily effect a radical cure; the same, too, with %0apains and contractions of the sinews, occasioned by cold. Ap¬ %0aplied with oil, they are useful for contusions, and with vinegar %0aand nitre, for fleshy excrescences upon the bones : in combina¬ %0ation with oil, they are good, too, for wounds inflicted by scor¬ %0apions and dogs. The ashes of the bark, employed by them¬ %0aselves, restore the hair to such parts of the body as have suf¬ %0afered from the action of fire. %0a%0aCHAP. 4 . —OMPHACIUM EXTRACTED FROM THE VINE : FOURTEEN %0aREMEDIES. %0a%0aWe have already mentioned, when speaking of the com¬ %0aposition of unguents, how omphacium is made from the grape, %0awhen it is just beginning to form : we shall now proceed to %0aspeak of its medicinal properties. Omphacium heals ulcerations %0aof the humid parts of the body, such as the mouth, tonsillary %0a%0a« This cannot be the bryony, Fee says, but simply a variety of the gi-ape %0avine with white fruit. See further in c. 5 of this Book. %0a%0a' “ Impetigines.” , -n/ r %0a%0aAlkaline ashes, which would differ but very little, says, from those %0aof other vegetable productions. , • . . %0a%0a9 This statement as to the caustic properties of the ashes is based upon %0atruth. %0a%0a%0a460 %0a%0a%0aPLIXr’s NA.TFKAL HISTORY. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXIII. %0a%0a%0aelands, and generative organs, for examjde; it is verj’good, %0atoo, for the sight, for rough spots upon the eyelids, ulcers at the %0acorners of the eyes, films upon the eyes, running sores on all %0aparts of the bod)’, cicatrizations” slow in forming, and purulent %0adischarges from the ears. The powerful action of omphacium %0ais modified by the admixture of honey or raisin wine. It is %0avery useful, too, for dysentery, spitting of blood, and quinsy. %0a%0aCHAP. 5.-CENANTHE : TWENTY-ONE REMEDIES. %0a%0a!Next to omphacium comes cenanthe, a product of the wild %0avine, described by us already ” when treating of the unguents. %0aThe most esteemed kind is that of Syria, the produce of the %0awhite vine in the vicinity of the mountains of Antiochia and %0aLaodicea in particular. Being of a cooling, astringent nature, %0ait is used for sprinkling upon sores, and is employed as a to¬ %0apical application for diseases of the stomach. It acts also as a %0adiuretic, and is good for maladies of the liver, head-ache, %0adysentery, cceliac afi'ections, and attacks of cholera ; for nausea, %0ait is taken in doses of one obolus in vinegar. It acts as a desic¬ %0acative upon running eruptions of the head, and is extremely %0aefiicacious for maladies of the humid parts of the body ; hence %0ait is that it is employed, with honey and saffron, for ulcers of %0athe mouth, and for diseases of the generative organs and the %0afundament. It arrests looseness of the bowels, and heals erup¬ %0ations of the eyelids and runnings at the eyes : taken with M’ine, %0ait cures derangements of the stomach, and with cold Avater, %0aspitting of blood. %0a%0aThe ashes of cenanthe are highly esteemed as an ingredient %0ain eye-salves, and as a detergent for ulcers, whitlows, and %0ahang-nailsto obtain these ashes, it is put into an oven, and %0aleft there till the bread is thoroughly baked. %0a%0aSaracemis, upon Dioscorides, B. v. c. 6, thinks that Pliny, in copying %0afrom the Greek, has made a mistake hei'e, and that he lias taken ovXuv, %0athe “gums,” for ov\t), u “cicatrix;” the corresponding passage in %0aDioscorides being ovXa TrXaSupa, “flaccidity,” or “humidity of the %0agums.” %0a%0aIn B. xii. c. 61. See also B. xiii. c. 2, B, xiv. c. 18, and B, xv. c. 7. %0aCEiianthc, or vine-blossom, possesses no active medicinal properties, and %0athe statements made here by Pliny are in all probability unfounded. %0a%0aNot the white vine, or Bryonia alba of modern botany, but probably %0asome variety of the cultivated vine with white fruit. The flower of the %0abryony is inodorous, and would be of no utility in the composition of %0aperfumes. “Pterygia.” %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 6.] %0a%0a%0aPllESEUVtD GRAPES. %0a%0a%0a461 %0a%0a%0aAs to inassaris,’® it is used as a perfume only. The renown %0aattached to all these preparations is due solely to the innate %0agreediness of mankind, which has racked its invention to gather %0athe productions of the earth before they have arrived at ma¬ %0aturity. %0a%0aCriAP. 6.—GRAPES, FRESH GATHERED. %0a%0aAs to grapes when allowed to gain maturity, the black ones %0ahave more marked properties than the others ; and hence it %0ais, tliat the wine made from them is not so agreeable. The %0awhite grapes, on the other hand, are sweeter, for, being trans¬ %0aparent, the air penetrates them with greater facility. %0a%0aGrapes fresh gathered are productive of flatulency, and dis¬ %0aturb the stomach and bowels; hence it is that the}' are avoided %0ain fevers, in large quantities more ])articularly. Indeed, they %0aare very apt to produce oppression of the head, and to bring on %0athe malady known as lethargy.” Grapes which have been %0agathered, and hdt to hang for some time, are much less'® hiju- %0arioiis, the exposure to the air rendering them beneficial even to %0athe stomach, and refreshing to the patient, as they are slightly %0acooling, and tend to remove nausea and qualmishness. %0a%0aCHAP. 7 . -VARIOUS KINDS OF PRESERVED GRAPES : ELEVEN %0a%0aFtEMEDIES. %0a%0aGrapes which have been preserved in w'ine or in must are %0atri'ing to the head, Next to the grapes which have been left %0ato hang in the air, are those which have been kept in chaff; %0abut as to those which have been preserved among grape husks, %0athey are injuriousto the head, the bladder, and the stomach. %0a%0aSee B. xii. c. 61. It was prepared from vine-blossoms gathered in %0aAfrica. %0a%0aTills remark is founded, in a great measure, upon fact. The skin of %0athe black grape contains a colouring principle in consider.able abundance, %0aand a small proportion of tannin ; that of tlie white grape possesses no %0acolouring principle, but a considerable quantity of tannin. The white %0agrape contains more saccharine matter than the black one, and they aro %0aboth of them of a laxative nature. %0a%0a” Little remarks, that under the name of “ lethargus,” a febrile m.alady %0ais probably meant, which belongs p>'obably to the class of pseudo-con¬ %0atinuous fevers. %0a%0aFee thinks that in reality there can be little or no difference in rheir %0aeffects, but that, being eaten in larger quantities at the vintage than after¬ %0awards, it stands to reason that the result will be different. %0a%0a’s The fermentation, producing a certain amount of alcohol, would %0anaturally produce this result. %0a%0a%0a462 %0a%0a%0aPliny’s natuhal uistouy. %0a%0a%0a[Buok XXIII. %0a%0a%0athough at the same time they arrest looseness of the bowels, %0aand are extremely good for patients troubled with spitting of %0ablood. When preserved in must, they are worse even in their %0aeffects than when kept among husks; boiled ^ must, too, ren¬ %0aders them injurious to the stomach. It is the opinion of medical %0awriters, that grapes kept*' in rain-water are the most whole¬ %0asome of all, even though they are by no means agreeable eating; %0afor the benefit of them is particularly experienced in burning %0apains of the stomach, biliousness arising from a disordered liver, %0avomiting of bile, and attacks of cholera, as also dropsy and %0aburning fevers. %0a%0aGrapes kept in earthen pots sharpen the taste, the stomach, %0aand the appetite; it is thought, however, that they are ren¬ %0adered a little heavy ** by the exhalations from the husks with %0awhich they are covered.** If vine-blossoms are given to %0apoultry, mixed with their food, they will never touch the %0agrapes.*' %0a%0aCHAP. 8.—CUTTINGS OF THE VINE : ONE REMEDY. %0a%0aSuch cuttings of the vine as have borne grapes, have an %0aastringent effect, when they are preserved in earthen *® pots, %0amore particularly. %0a%0aCHAP. 9.—GRAPE-STONES : SIX REMEDIES. %0a%0aGrape-stones, also, have a similar *® property ; it is through %0athem that wine is so apt to produce head-ache. Parched and %0athen pounded, they are beneficial for the stomach ; and this %0apowder is spidnkled, like polenta, in the beverage of patients %0asuffering from dysentery, coeliac affections, and derangements %0aof the stomach. A decoction of them is useful, also, as a fo¬ %0amentation for itch-scabs and prurigo. %0a%0a2® “ Sapamust boiled down to one-third. %0a%0a2* This, as Fee remarks, is quite impossible; grapes put in rain-water %0awould spoil immediately, and become totally unfit to eat. %0a%0aBy the transformation, namely, of the juices into alcohol. %0a%0a2® See B. xiv. c. 3. %0a%0a2* A notion quite unfounded, as Fee remarks. See B. xiv. c. 18. %0a%0a23 A prejudice equally destitute of foundation. %0a%0a2fi Grape-stones have an astringent effect, and Fee states that in modern %0atimes an oil is extracted from them of an agreeable fiavour, and applicable %0ato many economical purposes. They are no longer used in medicine. %0a%0a%0aChap. 12.] %0a%0a%0ahaisixs. %0a%0a%0a463 %0a%0a%0aCHAP, 10. —GEAPR-IIUSKS : EIGHT REMEDIES. %0a%0aGrape-husks, used by themselves, are less injurious to the %0ahead and bladder than grape-stones are : beaten up with salt, %0athey form an excellent liniment for inflammations of the ma- %0aniillse. A decoction of them, taken in drink, or employed as %0aa fomentation, is good for inveterate dysentery, and coeliac af¬ %0afections. %0a%0aCHAP. 11.-THE GHAPES OF THE THEKIACA : FOUR REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe grape of the theriaca, of which we have already made %0amention*’ on the appropriate occasion, is eaten by way of anti¬ %0adote to the stings of serpents. It is recommended, too, to eat %0athe j’oung shoots of this tree, and to apply them topically. %0aThe wine and vinegar made from these grapes are productive %0aof a similar salutary effect.*® %0a%0aCHAP. 12. —RAISINS, OR ASTAPHIS : FOURTEEN REMEDIES. %0a%0aRaisins, the name given to which is “ astaphis,” would be %0ainjurious to the stomach, abdomen, and intestines, were it not %0afor the stones within them, which act as a corrective.*® When %0athe stones are removed, raisins, it is thought, are beneficial to %0athe bladder, and good for cough in the last case, the raisin %0aof the white grape is considered the best. Raisins are good %0aalso for the trachea and the kidneys, and the wine made from %0athem is particularly efiicacious for the sting of the serpent %0acalled haemorrhois.®’ In combination with meal of cummin or %0acoriander, they are employed topically for inflammations of the %0atestes. For carbuncles and diseases of the joints, the stones %0aare remoAmd, and the raisins are pounded with rue; if used %0afor ulcers, the sores must be first fomented with wine. %0a%0aUsed with the stones, raisins are a cure for epinyctis, honey¬ %0acomb ulcers,** and dysentery; and for gangrenes they are applied %0atopically with radish rind and honey, being first boiled in oil. %0aThey are used with panax,** for gout and loose nails; and they %0a%0aIn B. xiv. c. 22. j i %0a%0a28 Hence the name “ theriaca,” from ei/p, a “ wild animal,” and uKtopai, %0a“ to cure.” %0a%0a28 Hy reason, probably, of their astringent properties. %0a%0a8® Though no longer used medicinally, they are still considered to be %0agood pectorals. See B. xx. cc. 23^aiid 81. %0a%0a82 “ Ceriaknown in modem medicine as “ tavus.' %0a%0a88 The Pastiiiaca opopanax of Linnseus. See B. xii. c. 67. %0a%0a%0a464 %0a%0a%0aPliny’s natuual in stout. %0a%0a%0a[Hook XXIII. %0a%0a%0aare sometimes eaten by themselves, in combination with pep. %0aper, for the purpose of cleansing the mouth and clearing tlie %0abrain. %0a%0aCHAP. 13 -THE ASTAPnrS.^GRIA, OTnEKWISE CALLED STAPHIS OU %0a%0aXAMINIA : TWELVE REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe wild astaphis, otherwise called staphis,** is by some per¬ %0asons erroneously called “ uva taminia;”*® for it is altogether a %0adistinct plant from the other. It has a black, ujmight stem, with %0aleaves resembling those of the labrusca,^ and bears what we may %0acall a pod,^’ rather than a grape, green, similar to a chick-pea %0ain appearance, and enclosing a kernel of triangular form. The %0afruit of it ripens with the vintage and turns black, while the %0aberries of the taminia,^® as is well known, are red ; this last, %0atoo, as we are aware, grows only in shaded spots, while the %0awild astaphis, on the other hand, loves a site that is exposed %0ato the sun. %0a%0aI Avould not recommend any one to use the kernels’'' of the %0awild astaphis as a purgative, as it is very doubtful whether they %0amight not choke the patient; nor would I advise them to be %0aemployed for the purpose of attenuating the phlegm, as they %0aare extremelj’^ irritating to the throat. Ileaten up, however, and %0aapplied topically, they kill vermin''® in the head and other parts %0aof the body, more particularly if they are used with sanda- %0arach; they are very useful, too, for itch-scabs and prurigo. A %0adecoction of the kernels is made with vinegar, for the cure of %0atooth-ache, diseases of the ears, cicatrices^' that are slow in %0ahealing, and running sores. %0a%0aThe blossoms of the plant are beaten up and taken in wine %0a%0a^ Identified with the Delphinium staphis agria of Linnajus. %0a%0a“Taininian grape.” Or wild vine. %0a%0aThe fruit is formed of three ohlong capsules, containing a triangular %0aseed of black hrown colour, about the size of a kidney bean. %0a%0aThis is not the white vine or bryony, mentioned in c. 16 of this %0aBook, but the Tamus communis of Linnaeus. %0a%0aThe seeds, which are remarkably pungent and powerful in tlicir %0aeflfects, are only used, at the present day, in medicinal preparations for %0acattle. %0a%0aThis is still done at the present day; to which it is indebted for its* %0aFrench name I’herbe pediculaire, or louse-plant. %0a%0aPliny seems again to have fallen into the error , of mistaking ov\ov, %0athe “ gums ” for oo\/), a “cicatrix the corresponding passage in Dios- %0acorides, B. iv. c. Id6, being “ defluxions of the gurus.” %0a%0a%0aChap. 15.] %0a%0a%0aTHE SALICASTJIUM. %0a%0a%0a48.5 %0a%0a%0afor stings^* inflicted by serpents ; but, as to. the seed, I would %0astrongly recominend its rejection, on account of its extremely %0apungent properties. Some persons give to this plant the name %0aof “ pituitaria,”^® and use it as a common application lor %0astings inflicted by serpents. %0a%0aCHAP. 14 . - THE LABKUSCA, OU WILD TINE : TWEI.TE REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe labrusca, too, produces an (Enanthe, which has been %0adescribed at sufficient length already by the Greeks the la- %0abriisca is known as the wild vine.^® The leaves of it are thick %0aaud of a whitish colour, the stem is jointed, and the bark fuU %0aof fissures : it bears grapes of a scarlet*® hue, like the coccus, %0awhich are made use of by females for the purpose of improving %0athe complexion, and removing spots upon the face. Pounded %0awith the leaves and the juice extracted from the tree, these %0agrapes are usefully employed for the treatment of lumbago %0aand sciatica. A decoction of the root*' in water, taken in two %0acyathi of Goan wine, promotes an alvine evacuation of aqueous %0asecretions; for whicli reason it is prescribed for dropsy.* %0a%0aI am inclined to think that this is the plant that is com¬ %0amonly known as the “uva taminia;’’*® it is in great request as %0aan amulet, and is employed, though as a gargle only, in cases %0aof spitting blood; for which purpose, salt, thyme, and oxymel %0aare added to it, care being taken not to swallow any of the %0amixture. It is generally looked upon as nnsafe to employ it as %0aa purgative. %0a%0aCHAP. 15 . -THE S-ALICASTRUM : TWELVE REMEDIES. %0a%0aThere is another plant,*® similar to the labrusca, but found %0aThey would be of no use whatever, Fee says, for such a purpose. %0a%0a*^ As tending to carry off “ pituita,” or phlegm. %0a%0a** In B. .vii. c. 61. %0a%0a*'’ “Ampelos agria.” Fee observes, that this Chapter is full of errors, %0aPliny beginning by speaking of the wild vine, the variety Labrusca of the %0aVitis vinifera of Linnajus, and then proceeding to describe what is really %0athe Bryonia dioica