 • In contradistinction to the fruits which hang from trees. %0a%3c %0a%3c * See B. xvii. c. 18. ® In xii. cc. 60 and 61. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 458 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c PLINy’s NA.TUUAL UI3T0IIY. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [liook XXIII, %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c it is I that produce for him tlie flowing wine and the trickling %0a%3c oil, it is I that ripen the date and other fruits in numhers so %0a%3c varied ; and all this, not insisting, like the earth, on their pur¬ %0a%3c chase at the cost of fatigues and labours. No necessity do I %0a%3c create for ploughing with the aid of oxen, for beating out %0a%3c upon the threshing-floor, or for bruising under the millstone, %0a%3c and all in order that man may earn his food at some indefinite %0a%3c time by this vast expenditure of toil. As for me, all my gifts %0a%3c are presented to him ready prepared: for no anxieties or %0a%3c fatigues do they call, but, on the contrary, they offer them¬ %0a%3c selves spontaneously, and even fall to the ground, if man %0a%3c should be too indolent to reach them as they hang.” Vying %0a%3c even with herself, Pomona has done still more for our juac- %0a%3c tical advantage than for the mere gratification of our pleasures %0a%3c and caprices. [ %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 3.—THE LEAVES AND SHOOTS OF THE VINE : SEVEN %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ^The leaves and shoots of the vine, employed with polenta, %0a%3c allay head-ache and reduce inflammations :® the leaves, too, %0a%3c applied b}' themselves with cold water, are good for burning %0a%3c pains in the stomach ; and, used with barley-meal, are excel¬ %0a%3c lent applications for diseases of the joints. The shoots, beaten %0a%3c up and applied, have the property of drying up all kinds of %0a%3c running tumours, and the juice extracted from them is used %0a%3c as an injection for the cure of dysentery. The tears of the %0a%3c vine, M^hich would appear to be a sort of gum, will heal le¬ %0a%3c prous sores, lichens, and itch-sca